```kotlin
class Whatever {

    private companion object {
        val Troll = {
            (null as Whatever).troll
        }
    }

    private val troll = Troll()

}

class Troll
```

Some observations.
1. Commenting `(null as Whatever).troll` eliminates error. But uncommenting and adding Unit as lambda return value â€” not.
2. Assigning to `troll` a value of obvious type (`Unit`, `""`, etc) eliminates error.
3. Adding explicit type declaration (`val Troll: () -> Unit = { ...`) eliminates error.
4. Even when lambda body is empty and no compiler error, `val troll = Troll()` gets inferred to `Unit`. `val troll: Troll = Troll()` is incorrect. No way to reference a class with the same name, only Companion's property.

Reproduced in two different projects:
1. Gradle, Android plug-in, Android SDK.
2. Kotlin project with IDEA build system, JDK 9.

